description:
From Middle French migration and its source, Latin migrātiō, from the participle stem of migrō (“I migrate”).
Morphologically migrate +‎ -ion

entries.meaning: An instance of moving to live in another place for a while.
Seasonal moving of animals, as mammals, birds or fish, especially between breeding and non-breeding areas.

examples: The migration of lead from a can to the food inside it can cause lead poisoning.

entries.meaning: (computing) Instance of changing a platform from an environment to another one.
(biochemistry) The movement of cells in particular directions to specific locations.
